{"id":"1812.07637","submitter":"Aidan Brown","authors":"Arshia Zarrin, David A. Sivak, and Aidan I. Brown","title":"Breaking time-reversal symmetry for ratchet models of molecular machines","comments":"8 pages, 5 figures","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 99, 062127 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.99.062127","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech q-bio.SC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Biomolecular machines transduce free energy from one form to another to\nfulfill many important roles inside cells, with dissipation required to achieve\ndirected progress. We investigate how to break time-reversal symmetry at a\ngiven dissipation cost by using deterministic protocols to drive systems over\nsawtooth potentials, which have frequently been used to model molecular\nmachines as ratchets. Time asymmetry increases for sawtooth potentials with\nhigher barriers and for driving potentials of intermediate width. For systems\ndriven over a sawtooth potential according to a protocol, we find that\nsymmetric sawtooths maximize time asymmetry, while earlier work examining\nratchet models of molecular machines required asymmetric sawtooth potentials to\nachieve directed behavior. This distinction arises because deterministically\ndriven machines are externally provided with direction, while autonomous\nmachines must generate directed behavior.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 18 Dec 2018 20:47:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 29 May 2019 16:17:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-03"}
